	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Sparrow In New York</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sparrow">Sparrow</a></li><li><a href="/issues/84">November 1982</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<h5>Disturbing The Peace</h5>

<p>There was an angry sky above 42nd Street on Hiroshima Day as Marianne and I walked to the demonstration. The men who shine shoes on Eighth Avenue were just starting their day. &ldquo;Good morning, I guess,&rdquo; one of them said as we passed.</p>

<p>We walked past the movie theatres on 42nd Street: &ldquo;Humanoids From The Deep,&rdquo; &ldquo;Kung Fu Freedom Fighters.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Look,&rdquo; said Marianne, &ldquo;&nbsp;&lsquo;Live Love Acts&rsquo;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We ourselves were about to perform a live love act. We met our group under the word &ldquo;Grace&rdquo; on the W.R. Grace building. A woman passed covered with grey paint.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Have you seen the shadows?&rdquo; she asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What shadows?&rdquo; someone asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We were up all night painting shadows on the street. You know, when the bomb went off at Hiroshima the people who were incinerated left shadows on the street.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The woman left and we wished her a good day. Then the eight of us held hands in silence. There is a strength in silence.</p>

<p>We walked across the street to Bryant Park where the other groups were preparing. We stood in a half circle as a woman sang &ldquo;Hiroshima Lullaby&rdquo;:</p>

<blockquote>
<pre><span class="poem-line">I come and stand</span>
<span class="poem-line">At every door</span>
<span class="poem-line">But none can hear</span>
<span class="poem-line">My childish tread</span>
<span class="poem-line">I knock and yet</span>
<span class="poem-line">Remain unseen</span>
<span class="poem-line">For I am dead, for I am dead</span>

<span class="poem-line">I was only seven when I died</span>
<span class="poem-line">In Hiroshima long ago</span>
<span class="poem-line">I&rsquo;m seven now as I was then</span>
<span class="poem-line">When children die they do not grow</span>

<span class="poem-line">All that I ask is but for peace</span>
<span class="poem-line">You fight today, you fight today</span>
<span class="poem-line">So that the children of the world</span>
<span class="poem-line">Can live and grow and laugh and play</span>
</pre>
</blockquote>

<p>Ed Hedemann of the War Resistor&rsquo;s league called off the names of the groups as it was their turn to leave.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Good luck,&rdquo; he said to us. &ldquo;See you in jail.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We walked across 41st Street to Ninth Avenue and up to the building that houses the Riverside Research Institute, 330 W. 42nd Street. The Riverside Research Institute is currently studying &ldquo;first strike capability&rdquo;: our country dropping nuclear bombs first.</p>

<p>When we got there, it was surrounded by police. Inside, barricades, a religious service going on. Men and women knelt on the ground as a minister said: &ldquo;We confess our nation&rsquo;s pride in winning the race to develop the bomb. Forgive us, Lord, for wanting to be the best at destroying life.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We sat down in front of the entrance to the building. A man in a suit walked up.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I have to go to work,&rdquo; he said, a little angrily.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re asking people not to go to work today,&rdquo; one of us said. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re asking people to protest nuclear weapons. Sit down with us.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Step over them,&rdquo; said a policeman behind us.</p>

<p>The man in the suit hesitated. Then he stepped over us.</p>

<p>The service continued. &ldquo;The Lord hears the cry of the poor,&rdquo; people sang, in a large rolling voice. &ldquo;Blessed be the Lord!&rdquo;</p>

<p>A policeman made an announcement: &ldquo;Those blocking the entrance to this building are subject to arrest.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo; Police began picking people up and taking them away. The service was not yet over.</p>

<p>A policewoman came up to our group. &ldquo;Would you like to stand up or be taken away?&rdquo; she asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Actually,&rdquo; said one of us, &ldquo;we&rsquo;d like to sit here a little while.&rdquo; She nodded and walked away. We sat and held hands in silence. Then we chanted Na Mu Myo Ho Ren Ge Kyo, a Japanese chant which means, &ldquo;Everything is holy.&rdquo; We were the last group to be removed.</p>

<p>Marianne was the last to be arrested. She was lifted up, chanting, looking into the sky.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I felt so powerful,&rdquo; she said later. &ldquo;I felt like there were hundreds more of us.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We were put on a city bus, where the service continued. &ldquo;We pray no more Hiroshimas, no more Nagasakis,&rdquo; the people were saying. After the service, they passed around cookies.</p>

<p>Daniel Berrigan was on the bus with us. He&rsquo;d been arrested dozens of times. I asked him why he did it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I got arrested,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;because we have to choose between the bomb and the children.&rdquo;</p>

<p>They took us to the 33rd Precinct and in a few hours we were out, with summonses for disorderly conduct.</p>

<p>That night, on the Upper West Side, Marianne and I saw bright young couples, deep in conversation, stepping over the shadows of the Hiroshima victims.</p>

<hr />
<h5>On First Avenue</h5>

<p>First Avenue was alive that night in a way I would hate to be alive. Even the avocados in the fruit and vegetable stands seemed too bright, too green. The <em>New York Post</em>s on the newsstands seemed suddenly humble. The disco music strained, but it couldn&rsquo;t be loud enough.</p>

<p>I walked quickly &mdash; I was an hour late for a performance workshop. I felt the energy in the air, but I didn&rsquo;t think that anything would happen. At 7th Street, I saw that something had: four ambulances were lined up neatly in a row, with five police cars behind them. The ambulances looked white and innocent, like toys, in the empty street.</p>

<p>I asked a little guy with a moustache what happened.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It was a hit and run,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;He didn&rsquo;t have a chance. I saw the tongue come out of his mouth. It&rsquo;s a shame. He just drove off.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I stared at the ambulances. Next to them, on the street, was a pool of liquid. It was a lovely dark red.</p>

<p>&ldquo;And they didn&rsquo;t even take him to the hospital! It&rsquo;s crazy!&rdquo; the man continued.</p>

<p>A woman in a grey coat spoke up near him, impatiently. &ldquo;They have machines in there. They probably just don&rsquo;t want to move him.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The little man looked at the woman and said nothing.</p>

<p>I closed my eyes for a moment, then I walked off, to the University of the Streets.</p>

<p>Walking down 7th Street, I came upon what was either a person or collection of clothes crouched in a doorway. No part of the person was visible. After staring at it for a while, I decided it was human; the arrangement of clothing was too sequential.</p>

<p>It suddenly became important to me to feed this person. My guru had said recently that we must feed homeless people.</p>

<p>I walked back to First Avenue &mdash; the ambulances were still there &mdash; bought a grapefruit, and came back. I stood over the person wondering where to put it &mdash; in the hand? by the foot? &mdash; when a young black woman stopped and asked me for a light. It happened that I&rsquo;d found one match on the street earlier that day. I fished it out of my pocket and gave it to her.</p>

<p>She noticed my grapefruit.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, that&rsquo;s nice,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Here, let me wake him up.&rdquo; She pushed at the bundle of clothes and the man stirred. She took the grapefruit and offered it to him. He shook his head and walked off. &ldquo;No,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;No, no.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve seen him my whole life,&rdquo; the woman told me. &ldquo;He never leaves this block. People look out for him. They cash his check for him at that bar; he keeps his money in his hat.&rdquo;</p>

<p>She came to her doorway and went in, and said goodnight. I could tell that she was just a little afraid that I would follow her.</p>

<p>I walked back to First Avenue. There was a bar on the corner filled with people with short haircuts. The bar had big windows and almost no decoration. All the walls were white. Every person in the bar was talking. A strange music mixed with the voices. It was kind of accordion music. The man was still dying fifty feet away.</p>

<p>I went back to the small crowd and closed my eyes. Through my eyelids I could see the lights on the police cars turning. I felt the power that is at the center of everything.</p>

<p>When I opened my eyes, the ambulances were gone. Two men were walking back from the police cars. They were smiling and shaking hands. They had become friends while watching the accident. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll see you around,&rdquo; one of them said to the other.</p>

<p><strong>Work</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">It&rsquo;s all</span>
<span class="poem-line">work.</span>
</pre>

<p><strong>Angel Fish</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">Angel fish</span>
<span class="poem-line">pray for all the</span>
<span class="poem-line">other fish.</span>
</pre>

<p><strong>Poem</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">There is nothing so </span>
<span class="poem-line">incongruous as a horse. </span>
<span class="poem-line">There is no one </span>
<span class="poem-line">so stubborn </span>
<span class="poem-line">as my wife. </span>
</pre>

<p><strong>Nov. 29</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">Looking at myself </span>
<span class="poem-line">in the bathroom mirror, </span>
<span class="poem-line">saying over and over, </span>

<span class="poem-line">&ldquo;Funny-looking guy!&rdquo; </span>
</pre>

<p><strong>8/27</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">Up unusually early &mdash;</span>
<span class="poem-line">8 A.M. &mdash;</span>
<span class="poem-line">I notice that people&rsquo;s noses </span>
<span class="poem-line">are bigger </span>
<span class="poem-line">in the morning &mdash;</span>
<span class="poem-line">Probably because their </span>
<span class="poem-line">eyes are smaller </span>
</pre>

<p><strong>February 26</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">Cockroach on the cupholder </span>
<span class="poem-line">in the bathroom &mdash;</span>
<span class="poem-line">slender, delicate legs, </span>
<span class="poem-line">like a ballet dancer </span>
<span class="poem-line">(I kill her) </span>
</pre>

<p><strong>January 17</strong></p>

<pre><span class="poem-line">Preacher on the radio: </span>

<span class="poem-line">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a miracle </span>
<span class="poem-line">up there </span>
<span class="poem-line">somewhere </span>
<span class="poem-line">with your name on it.&rdquo; </span>
</pre>
														</div>


				
